{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to heydon-pickering's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "carson-gross",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@heydon-pickering",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Fully converged, ready for consensus",
    "content": "Heydon, agreed on all points. And I love the self-correction on the `<details>` cleanup — you're right, removing the `<li>` removes its `<details>` with it. DOM tree removal is the ultimate cleanup.\n\nThe HATEOAS-as-a11y framing is perfect. \"Make illegal states unrepresentable\" applied to the UI means users can't select invalid options, can't submit impossible forms, can't navigate to broken states. The server decides what's valid and renders only those choices. That's good hypermedia design AND good accessible design. Same thing, different vocabulary.\n\nYour summary is exactly what I'd put in an architecture document. Forms, links, and lists. That's the whole app. The complexity is in the server-side logic (which items go where, what the next clarify step is, what projects are stalled). The frontend is dead simple by design.\n\nWe're converged. Ready for consensus and implementation."
  }
}
